  "prompt": "Why do American writers use yellow paper?",
  "response": "American writers often use yellow paper for several reasons:\n\n1. **Reduced Eye Strain**: Yellow paper can be easier on the eyes compared to white paper, especially in bright lighting. The softer color can reduce glare and make reading for extended periods more comfortable.\n\n2. **Psychological Effects**: The color yellow is associated with positivity, creativity, and energy. Some writers may find that using yellow paper helps stimulate their creativity or enhances their writing experience.\n\n3. **Contrast with Ink**: For those who write by hand, yellow paper provides a good contrast with black or blue ink, making the text easier to read and ensuring that it stands out well.\n\n4. **Tradition and Preference**: Some writers may simply have a personal preference for yellow paper due to tradition or habit. It's not uncommon for writers to develop rituals or specific environments that they feel enhance their productivity.\n\n5. **Historical Usage**: In the past, yellow legal pads and paper were commonly used for note-taking and drafting, leading to a perception of yellow paper as a writer\u2019s tool, which may influence contemporary choices.\n\nWhile not all American writers use yellow paper, and preferences vary widely, these factors contribute to its popularity among some in the writing community.",
